{% extends "base.twig" %}

{% block title %}Say it with SoundCloud{% endblock %}
{% block head %}
  {{ parent() }}

{% endblock %}

{% block header %}
{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
  {% set breadcrumb %}
    <a href="{{ url_for('home') }}" class="unstyled">Home</a> / Hello SoundCloud
  {% endset %}
  {{ parent() }}
  <div class="container">
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-3"></div>
      <div class="col-6">
        <div id="say-it-with-songs-app"></div>
      </div>
      <div class="col-3"></div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="col-12">
        <p class="text-center">
          I've heard that you're using Scala and react.js at SoundCloud (among Ruby of course) and I have close
          to zero experience in both, so I thought it would be fun to dive into a new language and a framework.
          Since the introductory computer science course of my first semester in which we learned Haskell was quite
          some time ago, I found especially the functional parts of Scala very exciting. You can find both the
          <a href="https://github.com/chrisonntag/say-it-with-songs">Scala</a> backend (using cask and Jsoup) and
          the small <a href="https://github.com/chrisonntag/christophsonntag.com/tree/master/say-it-with-songs">react.js</a>
          app on my GitHub profile.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

{% endblock %}

{% block newsletter %}
{% endblock %}

{% block scripts %}
  <script src="{{ base_path() }}/js/say-it-with-songs.bundle.js"></script>
{% endblock %}